english:
  title: Two Poems Composed While Ill, Upon Plum Blossoms Beginning to Bloom Below the Scholar's Tower
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I stand alone before the Scholar's Tower, a wandering sage.
    When we meet and smile, it is as it was of old.
    The sedan palanquin slows to pass, yet hands reach back to comfort me—
    This year's spring wind blows far too fierce, unbalanced and wild.

    Spring's lethargy mingles with my illness, carrying me past the Clear Brightness Festival.
    Our official affairs drift dim and drowsy—sleep comes easily now.
    But as I chant verses by the plum tree, my spirit stirs with subtle longing,
    When suddenly the clerks cry out in haste to wake their master.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Scholar's Tower' (學士樓) refers to a prestigious location, likely where the author or his circle gathered.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Clear Brightness Festival' (清明) marks the traditional spring period of renewal, making the speaker's illness all the more poignant.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between the speaker's weakened state and the clerks' urgent call creates a gentle tension between solitude and duty.
